[src:neovim/neovim] The Neovim project was started in 2014 by Thiago de Arruda as an effort to completely rework the outdated Vim source code as "Vim's rebirth of the 21st century" after a patch to Vim adding support for multi-threading was rejected.
[src:neovim/neovim] Neovim had a successful fundraising in March 2014, supporting at least one full-time developer.
[src:neovim/neovim] Neovim is meant as a successor to Vim, not a replacement.
[src:neovim/neovim] As such, the project aims to build on top of Vim's features and source code while maintaining Vim's "character" and almost all of its features.
[src:neovim/neovim] Over the years, various technical improvements were made to the source code, such as making the source code slimmer and more optimized, making features such as search faster and making Neovim extensible with the addition of support for Lua scripting.
[src:neovim/neovim] Neovim has gained popularity in the development scene, and as of January 2026 Neovim gained almost 96 thousand stars on GitHub compared to Vim's almost 40 thousand.
[src:neovim/neovim] In 2025, Neovim was voted the most admired development environment in the Stack Overflow developer survey for the fifth consecutive year.
[src:neovim/neovim] Neovim is designed with a client-server architecture, allowing users to use core functionality through alternative interfaces.
[src:neovim/neovim] Although Neovim is conventionally utilized through a terminal emulator, several graphical user interfaces have been developed as frontends.
[src:neovim/neovim] Since version 0.9 Neovim supports EditorConfig.
[src:neovim/neovim] Version 0.11 of Neovim improved handling of text completion and made the configuration of LSP servers easier.
[src:neovim/text-editor] A **text editor** is interactive software that allows a user to edit plain text, such as Notepad.
[src:neovim/text-editor] As source code is text, any text editor can be used to edit code, but a source-code editor is designed with features specifically intended for editing code.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Some provide integration with software development tools and provide a debugging environment.
[src:neovim/text-editor] There are important differences between plain text (created and edited by text editors) and rich text (such as that created by word processors or desktop publishing software).
[src:neovim/text-editor] Plain text exclusively consists of character representation.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Each character is represented by a fixed-length sequence of one, two, or four bytes, or as a variable-length sequence of one to four bytes, in accordance to specific character encoding conventions, such as ASCII, ISO/IEC 2022, Shift JIS, UTF-8, or UTF-16.
[src:neovim/text-editor] These conventions define many printable characters, but also non-printing characters that control the flow of the text, such as space, line break, and page break.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Plain text contains no other information about the text itself, not even the character encoding convention employed.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Plain text is stored in text files, although text files do not exclusively store plain text.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Since the early days of computers, plain text was (once by necessity and now by convention) generally displayed using a monospaced font, such that horizontal alignment and columnar formatting were sometimes done using whitespace characters.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Rich text can be saved in binary format (e.g.
[src:neovim/text-editor] DOC), text files adhering to a markup language (e.g.
[src:neovim/text-editor] RTF or HTML), or in a hybrid form of both (e.g.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Text editors are intended to open and save text files containing either plain text or anything that can be interpreted as plain text, including the markup for rich text or the markup for something else (e.g.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Before text editors existed, computer text was punched into cards with keypunch machines.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Physical boxes of these thin cardboard cards were then inserted into a card reader.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Magnetic tape, drum and disk card image files created from such card decks often had no line-separation characters at all, and assumed fixed-length 80- or 90-character records.
[src:neovim/text-editor] An alternative to cards was Punched tape.
[src:neovim/text-editor] It could be created by some teleprinters (such as the Teletype), which used special characters to indicate ends of records.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Some early operating systems included batch text editors, either integrated with language processors or as separate utility programs; one early example was the ability to edit SQUOZE source files for SCAT in the SHARE Operating System.
[src:neovim/text-editor] The first interactive text editors were "line editors" oriented to teletypes: teleprinter-style or typewriter-style terminals that mechanically printed both input and output on the same continuous roll of paper, without an illuminated display.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Commands (often a single keystroke) effected edits to a file at an insertion point, that the operator needed to keep track of, called the "cursor".
[src:neovim/text-editor] Edits were verified by typing a command to print a small section of the file, and periodically by printing the entire file.
[src:neovim/text-editor] In some line editors, the cursor could be moved by commands that specified the line number in the file, text strings (context) for which to search, and eventually regular expressions.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Line editors were major improvements over keypunching.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Some line editors could be used by keypunch; editing commands could be taken from a deck of cards and applied to a specified file.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Some common line editors supported a "verify" mode in which change commands displayed the altered lines.
[src:neovim/text-editor] An example configuration, circa 1975, was a Teletype Model 33 as a console to a PDP-11 using Version 6 Unix, manipulating text with the *ed*, the standard UNIX text editor.
[src:neovim/text-editor] When computer terminals with video screens became available, screen-based text editors (sometimes called just "screen editors") became common.
[src:neovim/text-editor] One of the earliest full-screen editors was O26, which was written for the operator console of the CDC 6000 series computers in 1967.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Another early full-screen editor was vi.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Written in the 1970s, it is still a standard editor on Unix and Linux operating systems.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Also written in the 1970s was the UCSD Pascal Screen Oriented Editor, which was optimized both for indented source code and general text.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Emacs, one of the first free and open-source software projects, is another early full-screen or real-time editor, one that was ported to many systems.
[src:neovim/text-editor] The 1977 Commodore PET was the first mass-market computer to feature a full-screen editor.
[src:neovim/text-editor] A full-screen editor's ease-of-use and speed (compared to the line-based editors) motivated many early purchases of video terminals.
[src:neovim/text-editor] The core data structure in a text editor is the one that manages the string (sequence of characters) or list of records that represents the current state of the file being edited.
[src:neovim/text-editor] While the former could be stored in a single long consecutive array of characters, the desire for text editors that could more quickly insert text, delete text, and undo/redo previous edits led to the development of more complicated sequence data structures.
[src:neovim/text-editor] A typical text editor uses a gap buffer, a linked list of lines (as in PaperClip), a piece table, or a rope, as its sequence data structure.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Some text editors are small and simple, while others offer broad and complex functions.
[src:neovim/text-editor] For example, Unix and Unix-like operating systems have the pico editor (or a variant), but many also include the vi and Emacs editors.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Microsoft Windows systems come with the simple Notepad, though many people—especially programmers—prefer other editors with more features.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Under Apple Macintosh's classic Mac OS there was the native TeachText later replaced by SimpleText in 1994, which was replaced in Mac OS X by TextEdit, which combines features of a text editor with those typical of a word processor such as rulers, margins and multiple font selection.
[src:neovim/text-editor] These features are not available simultaneously, but must be switched by user command, or through the program automatically determining the file type.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Most word processors can read and write files in plain text format, allowing them to open files saved from text editors.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Saving these files from a word processor, however, requires ensuring the file is written in plain text format, and that any text encoding or BOM settings will not obscure the file for its intended use.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Non-WYSIWYG word processors, such as WordStar, are more easily pressed into service as text editors, and in fact were commonly used as such during the 1980s.
[src:neovim/text-editor] The default file format of these word processors often resembles a markup language, with the basic format being plain text and visual formatting achieved using non-printing control characters or escape sequences.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Later word processors like Microsoft Word store their files in a binary format and are almost never used to edit plain text files.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Some text editors can edit unusually large files such as log files or an entire database placed in a single file.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Simpler text editors may just read files into the computer's main memory.
[src:neovim/text-editor] With larger files, this may be a slow process, and the entire file may not fit.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Some text editors do not let the user start editing until this read-in is complete.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Editing performance also often suffers in nonspecialized editors, with the editor taking seconds or even minutes to respond to keystrokes or navigation commands.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Specialized editors have optimizations such as only storing the visible portion of large files in memory, improving editing performance.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Some editors are programmable, meaning, e.g., they can be customized for specific uses.
[src:neovim/text-editor] With a programmable editor it is easy to automate repetitive tasks or, add new functionality or even implement a new application within the framework of the editor.
[src:neovim/text-editor] One common motive for customizing is to make a text editor use the commands of another text editor with which the user is more familiar, or to duplicate missing functionality the user has come to depend on.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Software developers often use editor customizations tailored to the programming language or development environment they are working in.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Emacs can even be programmed to emulate Vi, its rival in the traditional editor wars of Unix culture.
[src:neovim/text-editor] An important group of programmable editors uses REXX as a scripting language.
[src:neovim/text-editor] These "orthodox editors" contain a "command line" into which commands and macros can be typed and text lines into which line commands and macros can be typed.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Most such editors are derivatives of ISPF/PDF EDIT or of XEDIT, IBM's flagship editor for VM/SP through z/VM.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Among them are THE, KEDIT, X2, Uni-edit, and SEDIT.
[src:neovim/text-editor] A text editor written or customized for a specific use can determine what the user is editing and assist the user, often by completing programming terms and showing tooltips with relevant documentation.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Many text editors for software developers include source code syntax highlighting and automatic indentation to make programs easier to read and write.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Programming editors often let the user select the name of an include file, function or variable, then jump to its definition.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Some also allow for easy navigation back to the original section of code by storing the initial cursor location or by displaying the requested definition in a popup window or temporary buffer.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Some editors implement this ability themselves, but often an auxiliary utility like ctags is used to locate the definitions.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Most text editors provide methods to duplicate and move text within the file, or between files.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Cut, copy and paste are often integrated with a system clipboard.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Text editors provide extensive facilities for searching and replacing strings of text, either individually, or groups of files in opened tabs or a selected folder.
[src:neovim/text-editor] , and listing multiple results in one place.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Often—especially with older text editors—there is only one level of edit history remembered and successively issuing the undo command will only "toggle" the last change.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Modern or more complex editors usually provide a multiple-level history such that issuing the undo command repeatedly will revert the document to successively older edits.
[src:neovim/text-editor] A separate redo command will cycle the edits "forward" toward the most recent changes.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Ability to jump to a specified line number.
[src:neovim/text-editor] To define new commands or features as combinations of prior commands or other macros, perhaps with passed parameters, or with nesting of macros.
[src:neovim/text-editor] To retain options set by the user between editing session.
[src:neovim/text-editor] With names specified in, e.g., environment, profile, executed automatically at the beginning of an edit session or when opening a new file.
[src:neovim/text-editor] The ability to display multiple views of the same file, with independent cursor tracking, synchronizing changes among the windows but providing the same facilities as are available for independent files.
[src:neovim/text-editor] The ability to temporarily exclude sections of the text from view.
[src:neovim/text-editor] The ability to alter or insert data at a particular column, or to shift data to specific columns.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Reading or merging the contents of another text file into the file currently being edited.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Also, a case-shifting feature could translate to lowercase or uppercase.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Some advanced text editors allow the editor to send all or sections of the file being edited to another utility and read the result back into the file in place of the lines being "filtered".
[src:neovim/text-editor] and other text that appears in an organized or predictable format.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Editors generally allow users to customize the colors or styles used for each language element.
[src:neovim/text-editor] after one press navigated to the end of an on-screen row of text.
[src:neovim/text-editor] typically have dedicated cursor movement keys, as do keyboards on personal computers.
[src:neovim/text-editor] , have a dedicated field on the screen for entering commands as opposed to text.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Depending on the editor, the user may have to use cursor keys to switch between the command and text fields or the editor may interpret, e.g., specific function keys, as requests to switch.
[src:neovim/text-editor] (also known as prefix commands or sequence commands) Some editors treat a file as an array of text lines with associated line numbers or sequence numbers, and have a distinct line number field for each text field.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Some editors also support line macros, also known as prefix macros or sequence macros.
[src:neovim/text-editor] , some editors allow the sequence field to appear after the text field.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Text editors with additional functionality to facilitate the production of source code.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Includes so-called "orthodox editors" that are derivatives of Xedit.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Editors that implement folding without programing-specific features are usually called outliners (see below).
[src:neovim/text-editor] Folding can be considered a specialized form of outlining.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Designed to manage and streamline large programming projects.
[src:neovim/text-editor] They are usually only used for programming as they contain many features unnecessary for simple text editing.
[src:neovim/text-editor] that are assembled by the software controlling the site and do not compose a complete HTML document.
[src:neovim/text-editor] Allows multiple users to work on the same document simultaneously from remote locations over a network.
[src:neovim/text-editor] The changes made by individual users are tracked and merged into the document automatically to eliminate the possibility of conflicting edits.
[src:neovim/text-editor] , are targeted at a single programming language.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Vim's documentation describes it as an improved form of the older vi text editor (though it is built from a distinct codebase).
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] In release information, the author originally implied that Vim was an abbreviation for "Vi IMitation", but later, the expansion was changed to "Vi IMproved" because, as described by the author, the functionality had increased beyond that of a clone of vi.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Some sources indicate the change happened with v2.0, but conflicting information (including from author) suggests the change happened as early as v2.0 and as late as v3.0.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Since its original release for the Amiga, Vim has been ported to many environments including Atari MiNT, BeOS, MS-DOS, Windows starting from Windows NT 3.1, OS/2, OS/390, MorphOS, OpenVMS, QNX, RISC OS, Linux, BSD, and Classic Mac OS.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Independent ports of Vim are available for Android and iOS.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Vim has been and continues to be popular for software development.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] In 2018, it was voted the most popular editor amongst *Linux Journal* readers.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] In 2015, the Stack Overflow developer survey found it to be the third most popular text editor, and, in 2019, the fifth most popular development environment.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] In 1988, Bram Moolenaar began work on what would become Vim.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] He used the codebase for the Stevie editor ported to Amiga (by Tony Andrews et al.) as a starting point.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Version 1.14 (completed 2 November 1991) became the first public release.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] It was distributed via Fish Disk #591 in January 1992.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Vim is released under the Vim license, which includes some charityware clauses that encourage users who enjoy the software to consider donating to children in Uganda.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] The Vim license is compatible with the GNU General Public License through a special clause allowing distribution of modified copies under the GNU GPL version 2.0 or later.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Building upon the core vi functionality, Vim provides a user experience that integrates keyboard-entered command input with a full-screen editing experience.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Vim allows a user with a typical keyboard to keep their fingers on the home row, which can be an advantage for touch typing.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Via its GUI mode (called gVim), it presents an interface with a more modern experience including aspects such as menus, toolbars and icons.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] The full functionality is still expressed through its command line mode.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Vim has a built-in help facility accessible via the `:help` command.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] The Vim tutorial for beginners, called vimtutor, is usually installed alongside Vim, but is a separate executable and can be run separately.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] The Vim Users' Manual details Vim's features and can be read from within Vim, or found online.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Vim features various special memory entries called registers (not to be confused with hardware or processor registers).
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] When cutting, deleting, copying, or pasting text the user can choose to store the manipulated text in a register.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] There are 36 general-purpose registers associated with letters and numbers ([a-z0-9]) and a range of special ones that either contain special values (current filename, last command, etc.) or serve a special purpose.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Like vi, Vim supports multiple editing modes.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Depending on the mode, entered characters are either processed as command input or inserted as text.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Vim is customizable and extensible, making it attractive to those who want control and flexibility in a text editing environment.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Users can execute complex commands with *key bindings*, which can be customized and extended.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] The *recording* feature allows for the creation of macros to automate sequences of keystrokes and call internal or user-defined functions and mappings.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Abbreviations, similar to macros and key mappings, facilitate the expansion of short strings of text into longer ones and can also be used to correct mistakes.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Vim also features an *easy* mode for users wanting a simpler user experience.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] There are many plugins available that extend or add new functionality to Vim.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] These plugins are usually written in Vim's internal scripting language, vimscript (also known as VimL), but can be written in other languages as well.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] There are projects bundling together complex scripts and customizations and aimed at turning Vim into a tool for a specific task or adding a major flavour to its behaviour.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Examples include Cream, which makes Vim behave like a click-and-type editor, or VimOutliner, which provides a comfortable outliner for users of Unix-like systems.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Vim provides many features beyond what vi provides.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Vim continually saves information to a file that allows for recovering from a crash.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Generally, the file extension is ".swp", but if the user tries to open a file when the recovery file already exists, then Vim notifies the user of the condition.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] If the user confirms to proceed, Vim uses a different extension to form a name for a file that does not exist.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] The extensions are along the progression: ".swo", ".swn", ".swm", etc.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Vim provides a vi-compatibility mode that limits its functionality to be similar to that of vi.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] However, even in compatibility mode, Vim is not entirely compatible with vi as specified by POSIX.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] For example, Vim does not support vi's open mode.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Vim's developers state that it is "very much compatible with Vi".
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Version 9.0 added **Vim9 script**, a new script language closer to commonly used languages.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Vim macros can contain a sequence of *normal-mode* commands, but can also invoke ex commands or functions written in Vim script for more complex tasks.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Almost all extensions (called plugins or more commonly scripts) of the core Vim functionality are written in Vim script, but plugins can also utilize other languages like Perl, Python, Lua, Ruby, Tcl, or Racket.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] These plugins can be installed manually, or through a plugin manager such as Vundle, Pathogen, or Vim-Plug.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] Vim script files are stored as plain text, similarly to other code, and the filename extension is usually `.vim`.
[src:neovim/vim-text-editor] One notable exception to that is Vim's config file, `.vimrc`.
